- content_for :hero do
  .jumbotron(style="border-radius: 0px")
    .col-md-6.text-center(style="margin-top: 2em")
      %h2(style="color: #555; font-size: 3em")
        Make your ideas real. Even the unthinkable ones.
        %p
          %small(style="font-size: 0.9em")
            Learn to design 3D printable modeling through programming

.row
  .col-md-offset-1.col-md-4
    %img(src="/images/title_cover.png")

  .col-md-offset-1.col-md-5
    %h2
      Make your ideas real.
    %hr/
    .lead(style="margin-bottom: 2em")
      :markdown
        Nowadays, it's easier than ever to make your ideas physically real. All you need
        is to design a 3D model to feed into a 3D printer. But if mainstream CAD 
        software seems hard to learn and too expensive, then it's time to learn from 
        _Designing with OpenSCAD_.

    %h2
      Even the unthinkable ones.
    %hr/
    .lead
      :markdown
        New technologies allow us to do things we weren't able to do before, easier,
        cheaper, and faster. Inevitably, they allow us the possibility of changing
        established social order and power structure. What are the things we can do 
        with 3D printing that people don't want us to do?


.row.bar-section
  .col-md-12.text-center
    %h2
      Convinced already? 
      &nbsp;
      %a.btn.btn-success(href="https://leanpub.com/designing_with_openscad/packages/book/purchases/new")
        Buy eBook from $9.99

.row
  .col-md-offset-2.col-md-8.text-center
    %h2
      What is OpenSCAD?
    %p.lead
      OpenSCAD is a free and simple programming language
      %br/
      used to make 3D models for 3D printing.
  .col-md-4
    %h3.text-center
      Combine 3D shapes.
    :markdown
      OpenSCAD is a declarative programming language. That means you describe _what_
      to build, rather than _how_ to build it.
    %pre
      :preserve
        difference() {
          cube(30, center = true);
          sphere(20);
        }
  .col-md-4
    %h3.text-center
      To make 3D models.
    :markdown
      OpenSCAD creates models with no holes, so it's readable by 3D printers without
      any need to fix them--simplifying your toolchain.
    %img(src="/images/make_model.png")
  .col-md-4
    %h3.text-center
      For Free.
    :markdown
      OpenSCAD is open source software. It's both free as in speech and free as in beer.
      It's available on Windows, Mac, and Linux.
    %span(style="font-size: 8em")
      %i.fa.fa-windows
      %i.fa.fa-apple
      %i.fa.fa-linux


.row
  .col-md-offset-2.col-md-8
    %h2
      Programming is literacy.
    %hr/
    .lead
      :markdown
        Software is eating the world. Every industry is changing as software changes the
        way we live, work, and play.  OpenSCAD is a good start for learning how to 
        program, as a stepping stone to participating in the future. 


.row.bar-section.text-center
  .col-md-12
    %h2(style="margin-bottom: 1em")
      Why code to make 3D models?
  .col-md-4
    %h3
      Easy to learn.
    %div(style="font-size: 4em; margin: 0.25em 0em")
      %i.fa.fa-thumbs-o-up
    %p
      There's only 10 modules to learn in order to be dangerous in OpenSCAD. That makes
      it easy to get started without learning a complicated interface.
  .col-md-4
    %h3
      Collaborate on designs.
    %div(style="font-size: 4em; margin: 0.25em 0em")
      %i.fa.fa-code-fork
    %p
      Unlike mainstream CAD program files, OpenSCAD is code and we can collectively
      upon previous designs by leveraging git and other modern tools
      to collaborate.
  .col-md-4
    %h3
      Parametric models.
    %div(style="font-size: 4em; margin: 0.25em 0em")
      %i.fa.fa-pencil
    %p
      You can build parametric models with OpenSCAD, so if a dimension changes, you
      don't have to redesign the entire part. Just change a variable, and you're done.


